<h2><a href="http://forthescience.org/blog/2011/08/20/pac-mecium-and-other-games/" rel="bookmark">Pac-mecium and other games</a></h2>
<span class="submitted">August 20, 2011 &#8212; Stefano Borini </span>
<div class="content">
<p>This is a rather peculiar use of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paramecium">paramecia</a>: by directing their preferential swimming movement by means of an applied electric field (a property called <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taxis#Galvanotaxis_.2F_electrotaxis">galvanotaxis</a>) we can use them as player characters in videogames. I don&#8217;t expect this to become common gaming, though.</p>
<p><iframe width="500" height="375" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/Pdx7BkYSCq4?feature=oembed" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></p>
</div>
<div class="meta">
Posted in <a href="http://forthescience.org/blog/category/topics/biology/" title="View all posts in Biology" rel="category tag">Biology</a>.  <span>Comments Off</span> &#187;
</div>
