<h2><a href="http://forthescience.org/blog/2010/04/08/eight-molecules-that-changed-the-rules-of-the-game-cisplatin/" rel="bookmark">Eight molecules that changed the rules of the game: Cisplatin</a></h2>
<span class="submitted">April 8, 2010 &#8212; Stefano Borini </span>
<div class="content">
<h2><strong>Rule changed: revolutionized the treatment of cancer</strong></h2>
<p><strong> </strong><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Cisplatin-3D-vdW.png"><img class="aligncenter" title="Cisplatin" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/77/Cisplatin-3D-vdW.png/120px-Cisplatin-3D-vdW.png" alt="Cisplatin" width="120" height="104" /></a></p>
<p>Cisplatin, formula [PtCl<sub>2</sub>(NH<sub>3</sub>)<sub>2</sub>] is a very simple compound of the precious metal platinum. It  revolutionized the treatment of some types of cancer, in some cases with almost total chance of success, and it can be considered to full extent the &#8220;penicillin for (only some, unfortunately) cancer treatment&#8221;. <a href="http://forthescience.org/blog/2010/04/08/eight-molecules-that-changed-the-rules-of-the-game-cisplatin/#more-430" class="more-link">(more&hellip;)</a></p>
</div>
